In the 25 years since the initial discovery that acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS) is caused by the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV), the disease has grown into a global infectious disease.1 HIV is a pathogenic retrovirus and requires reverse transcriptase (RT) to copy its single-stranded RNA genome into a double-stranded DNA copy for integration in the host cell.2 Therefore, RT of AIDS virus has been the most important candidate for the treatment of AIDS. In the search for an effective chemotherapeutic agent of HIV infections for targeting RT, initial attempts were focused on the development of 2′,3′-dideoxynucleosides (ddNs) and 2′,3′-didehydro-2′,3′-dideoxynucleosides (d4Ns).3, 4 Among them, the nucleoside RT inhibitors (NRTIs)5 such as 3′-azido-3′-deoxythymidine (AZT),6 2′,3′-dideoxyinosine (ddI),7 2′,3′-dideoxycytidine (ddC),8
l-2′,3′-dideoxy-3′-thiacytidine (3TC)9 and 2′,3′-didehydro-2′,3′-dideoxythymidine (d4T)10 have been widely used to treat AIDS patients (Fig. 1
